column2: or a smaller holding facility at 410 Fallsway. The majority of abandoned vehicles
column3: scofflaw vehicles and cars that are towed as a result of an accident or police activity are taken to the Main Impound Storage Facility. Vehicles that are illegally parked along major city gateways during peak hours (rush hour) are placed at the Fallsway lot for up to 48 hours. If the vehicle is not retrieved from the facility within 48 hours
column4: it is then moved to the Pulaski Highway lot where storage fees may be assessed. Vehicles remaining at the Fallsway facility by the close of business each Friday will also be moved to Pulaski Highway.;56;07/29/2020 10:06:00 PM +0000;09/14/2020 10:00:00 AM +0000;Transportation;vehicle

https://data.baltimorecity.gov/d/a4sr-x5f7;a4sr-x5f7;true;false;;data.baltimorecity.gov;gis map;Bike_Lane_Facilities_2020;"This layer represents the existing bike facilities throughout the City of Baltimore
column2: as recognized by the Bike Baltimore program of the Baltimore City Department of Transportation. The existing bike facilities include on-street facilities
column3: separated facilities
column4: and multi-use trails where bicycle and scooter use is permitted. This layer contains attribute fields for Name

column1: The Name field indicates the name of the street or trail of the bike facility.
The Segment Miles field indicates the length in miles of the individual segment.
The Category field indicates the type of facility represented
column2: with the following values:

column1: ?	Separated Bike Lane: A lane designated for bike travel only and separated from the vehicular travel lanes by a buffer and flex posts or other barrier. This type of facility is indicated by painted lines
column2: a buffer
column3: pavement bike symbols

column1: ?	Bike Boulevard: A low traffic roadway which is shared by bikes and automobiles
column2: and is improved with traffic calming measures that promote bike usage and reduce vehicle speed
column3: such as bike-friendly speed bumps. This facility is indicated by pavement bike symbols and signage.

column1: ?	Bike Lane: A lane designated for bike travel only
column2: indicated with painted lines
column3: pavement bike symbols

column1: ?	Shared Lane Markings or Signage: A roadway which is shared by bikes and vehicles
column2: indicated by pavement bike symbols or signage.

column1: ?	Shared Bus/Bike Lane: A shared lane designated for use by bikes
column2: buses
column3: and right-turning vehicles. This lane is indicated with red-painted pavement

column1: ?	Path or Sidepath: A multi-use path or sidepath of sufficient width to accommodate shared bike and pedestrian use
column2: not for use by motorized vehicles. This facility is separated from the roadway by a curb or by a natural surfaces buffer
column3: or runs through a park along paths or park roads closed to vehicles.

column1: https://data.baltimorecity.gov/d/8gnu-wkhp;8gnu-wkhp;true;false;;data.baltimorecity.gov;href;DOT Find My Tow;Cars that are towed within city limits are taken to either the Main Impound Storage Facility located at 6700 Pulaski Highway
column2: or a smaller holding facility at 410 Fallsway. The majority of abandoned vehicles
column3: scofflaw vehicles and cars that are towed as a result of an accident or police activity are taken to the Main Impound Storage Facility. Vehicles that are illegally parked along major city gateways during peak hours (rush hour) are placed at the Fallsway lot for up to 48 hours. If the vehicle is not retrieved from the facility within 48 hours
column4: it is then moved to the Pulaski Highway lot where storage fees may be assessed. Vehicles remaining at the Fallsway facility by the close of business each Friday will also be moved to Pulaski Highway.;17

column1: https://data.baltimorecity.gov/d/ifsa-6r6x;ifsa-6r6x;true;false;;data.baltimorecity.gov;gis map;Education and Youth (2010-2013)  - Shape;"BNIA-JFI tracks twenty seven indicators for elementary
column2: middle
column3: and high school students in an effort to measure the educational performance and youth engagement in Baltimore City. These indicators are grouped into the following seven categories: student enrollment and demographics; dropout rate and high school completion; student attendance
column4: suspensions and expulsions; elementary and middle school student achievement; high school performance; youth labor force participation; and youth civic engagement. The source of data for the Education and Youth section is provided by the Baltimore City Public School System
column5: the American Community Survey and the Baltimore City Board of Elections. The data provided by the Baltimore City Public Schools includes student address
column6: which allows BNIA-JFI to present data on educational performance by the neighborhood in which the student lives
column7: not by the school attended. This allows BNIA-JFI to examine the relationship between community conditions and educational performance. Education and Youth indicators may not be directly comparable to data provided by either the Baltimore City Public School System or the Maryland Department of Education due to several reasons including differences in methodology used to create indicators
column8: excluding students who cannot be matched between data files provided by BCPSS
column9: and excluding students whose home address cannot be geocoded. In the 2009-2010 school year
column10: 3.4% of the student addresses could not be matched or geocoded. This means that these students were not included in our analysis and not included in calculations for the City as a whole and therefore direct comparisons to data and results available through the Baltimore City Public Schools and the Maryland Report Card cannot be made.";384;05/14/2015 07:38:00 PM +0000;02/06/2017 04:54:00 AM +0000;Neighborhoods;education

column1: https://data.baltimorecity.gov/d/89ug-ztsx;89ug-ztsx;true;true;hyq3-8sxr;data.baltimorecity.gov;filter;myview;"This data set shows the location of Baltimore City's Tansitional and Emergency ""Homeless"" Shelter Facilities. However
column2: this is not a complete list. It is the most recent update (2008)
column3: and is subjected to change. The purpose of this data set is to aid Baltimore City organizations to best identify facilities to aid the homeless population. The data is broken down into two categories: Emergency Shelter and Transitional Housing. Please find the two definitions below. The first is simply ??_??_??_shelter??_?? and the second is a more involved program that is typically a longer stay. Emergency Shelter: Any facility with overnight sleeping accommodations
column4: the primary purpose of which is to provide temporary shelter for the homeless in general or for specific populations of homeless persons. The length of stay can range from one night up to as much as six months. Transitional Housing: a project that is designed to provide housing and appropriate support services to homeless persons to facilitate movement to independent living within 24 months. These data set was provided by Greg Sileo
column5: Director of the Mayor's Office of Baltimore Homeless Services.";616;04/10/2015 07:21:00 PM +0000;03/27/2014 11:52:00 PM +0000;Health;homeless

column1: https://data.baltimorecity.gov/d/5hd4-kcwf;5hd4-kcwf;true;true;aqgr-xx9h;data.baltimorecity.gov;map view;project;Motorists who drive aggressively and exceed the posted speed limit by at least 12 miles per hour will receive $40 citations in the mail. These citations are not reported to insurance companies and no license points are assigned. Notification signs will be placed at all speed enforcement locations so that motorists will be aware that they are approaching a speed check zone. The goal of the program is to make the streets of Baltimore safer for everyone by changing aggressive driving behavior. In addition to the eight portable speed enforcement units
column2: the city has retrofitted 50 red light camera locations with the automated speed enforcement technology.;369;04/02/2015 04:09:00 PM +0000;04/03/2014 11:24:00 PM +0000;Transportation;speed

column1: https://data.baltimorecity.gov/d/fxs7-4fed;fxs7-4fed;true;true;xzfj-gyms;data.baltimorecity.gov;filter;Bike Boulevard;BikeBaltimore is the Department of Transportation??_??s bike program. Managed by the Planning Section
column2: BikeBaltimore includes anything bike related including implementing the Bicycle Master Plan
column3: incorporating cycling in many transportation projects
column4: installing bike racks and coordinating cycling events. The Bicycle Master Plan was developed by the Department of Planning in 2006. With the implementation of the Bicycle Master Plan
column5: more bike facilities are appearing on city streets. There are many different types of bike facilities. Bike Lane: an area designated for bike travel only. The bike lane is a 5??_?? wide lane with a bike symbol indicating that only bikes should use that lane
column6: Sharrow: A roadway which is shared by bikes and automobiles. Cars should treat bikes as vehicles in the lane and pass when it is safe to do so
column7: Signed Route: A roadway with no pavement markings
column8: signed routes are used on low-traffic volume streets where cyclists can ??_??_??_take the lane??_??. Cars should pass bikes when it is safe to do so. Signed routes typically have mileage and destination markers with route adjustments along the way
column9: Floating Bike Lane: Used along off-peak temporary parking
column10: floating bike lanes adjust to the presence of parked cars. If parked cars are not present
column11: cyclists occupy the 5??_?? bike lane along the curb. When parked cars are present
column12: the cyclist travels in the designated area between the parked cars and vehicular travel lanes
column13: Share The Road: When space does not exist for bike lanes
column14: ??_??_??_SHARE THE ROAD??_?? signs are installed to remind motorists that cyclists may be present. Here cyclists are encouraged to use the shoulder of the road
column15: or travel to the right while avoiding ??_??_??_door zones??_?? and roadside hazards
column16: Shared Bus & Bike Lanes: On Pratt St
column17: these lanes are only available to buses

column1: https://data.baltimorecity.gov/d/vanx-ubga;vanx-ubga;true;false;;data.baltimorecity.gov;gis map;Hurricane Inundation Zone;"This file is generated as part of the Hazards Analysis within the Hurricane Evacuation Study for the Maryland Western Shore. Storm surge zones have been developed for category 1-4 hurricanes represented by the Saffir-Simpson Scale. The storm surge zones data used in this application were generated using the Sea
column2: Lake
column3: and Overland Surges from Hurricanes (SLOSH) model. SLOSH is a computerized model run by the National Weather Service to estimate storm surge heights resulting from historical
column5: or predicted hurricanes. The model creates its estimates by assessing the pressure
column9: and wind data from a storm. Graphical output from the model displays color-coded storm surge heights for a particular area. The calculations are applied to a specific locale's shoreline
column10: incorporating the unique bay and river configurations
column12: bridges
column14: and other physical features. The SLOSH MOM data is utilized. MOM is the ""Maximum of Maximum or ""Meows Of Meows"". MOM output represents the highest water level or the ""worst case scenario"" for the entire Slosh basin.";1

column1: https://data.baltimorecity.gov/d/dmhe-byd7;dmhe-byd7;true;true;hyq3-8sxr;data.baltimorecity.gov;filter;Baltimore City Shelters;"This data set shows the location of Baltimore City's Tansitional and Emergency ""Homeless"" Shelter Facilities. However
column2: this is not a complete list. It is the most recent update (2008)
column3: and is subjected to change. The purpose of this data set is to aid Baltimore City organizations to best identify facilities to aid the homeless population. The data is broken down into two categories: Emergency Shelter and Transitional Housing. Please find the two definitions below. The first is simply ??_??_??_shelter??_?? and the second is a more involved program that is typically a longer stay. Emergency Shelter: Any facility with overnight sleeping accommodations
column4: the primary purpose of which is to provide temporary shelter for the homeless in general or for specific populations of homeless persons. The length of stay can range from one night up to as much as six months. Transitional Housing: a project that is designed to provide housing and appropriate support services to homeless persons to facilitate movement to independent living within 24 months. These data set was provided by Greg Sileo
column5: Director of the Mayor's Office of Baltimore Homeless Services.";1

column3: 2012;"This data set shows the location of Baltimore City's Tansitional and Emergency ""Homeless"" Shelter Facilities. However
column4: this is not a complete list. It is the most recent update (2008)
column5: and is subjected to change. The purpose of this data set is to aid Baltimore City organizations to best identify facilities to aid the homeless population. The data is broken down into two categories: Emergency Shelter and Transitional Housing. Please find the two definitions below. The first is simply ??_??_??_shelter??_?? and the second is a more involved program that is typically a longer stay. Emergency Shelter: Any facility with overnight sleeping accommodations
column6: the primary purpose of which is to provide temporary shelter for the homeless in general or for specific populations of homeless persons. The length of stay can range from one night up to as much as six months. Transitional Housing: a project that is designed to provide housing and appropriate support services to homeless persons to facilitate movement to independent living within 24 months. These data set was provided by Greg Sileo

These citations are not reported to insurance companies and no license points are assigned. Notification signs will be placed at all speed enforcement locations so that motorists will be aware that they are approaching a speed check zone. The goal of the program is to make the streets of Baltimore safer for everyone by changing aggressive driving behavior. In addition to the eight portable speed enforcement units
column2: the city has retrofitted 50 red light camera locations with the automated speed enforcement technology.;77

column1: https://data.baltimorecity.gov/d/xzfj-gyms;xzfj-gyms;true;false;;data.baltimorecity.gov;dataset;Bike Lanes;BikeBaltimore is the Department of Transportation??_??s bike program. Managed by the Planning Section
column2: BikeBaltimore includes anything bike related including implementing the Bicycle Master Plan
column3: incorporating cycling in many transportation projects
column4: installing bike racks and coordinating cycling events. The Bicycle Master Plan was developed by the Department of Planning in 2006. With the implementation of the Bicycle Master Plan
column5: more bike facilities are appearing on city streets. There are many different types of bike facilities. Bike Lane: an area designated for bike travel only. The bike lane is a 5??_?? wide lane with a bike symbol indicating that only bikes should use that lane
column6: Sharrow: A roadway which is shared by bikes and automobiles. Cars should treat bikes as vehicles in the lane and pass when it is safe to do so
column7: Signed Route: A roadway with no pavement markings
column8: signed routes are used on low-traffic volume streets where cyclists can ??_??_??_take the lane??_??. Cars should pass bikes when it is safe to do so. Signed routes typically have mileage and destination markers with route adjustments along the way
column9: Floating Bike Lane: Used along off-peak temporary parking
column10: floating bike lanes adjust to the presence of parked cars. If parked cars are not present
column11: cyclists occupy the 5??_?? bike lane along the curb. When parked cars are present
column12: the cyclist travels in the designated area between the parked cars and vehicular travel lanes
column13: Share The Road: When space does not exist for bike lanes
column14: ??_??_??_SHARE THE ROAD??_?? signs are installed to remind motorists that cyclists may be present. Here cyclists are encouraged to use the shoulder of the road
column15: or travel to the right while avoiding ??_??_??_door zones??_?? and roadside hazards
column16: Shared Bus & Bike Lanes: On Pratt St
column17: these lanes are only available to buses

column1: https://data.baltimorecity.gov/d/aqgr-xx9h;aqgr-xx9h;true;false;;data.baltimorecity.gov;dataset;Fixed Speed Cameras;Motorists who drive aggressively and exceed the posted speed limit by at least 12 miles per hour will receive $40 citations in the mail. These citations are not reported to insurance companies and no license points are assigned. Notification signs will be placed at all speed enforcement locations so that motorists will be aware that they are approaching a speed check zone. The goal of the program is to make the streets of Baltimore safer for everyone by changing aggressive driving behavior. In addition to the eight portable speed enforcement units
column2: the city has retrofitted 50 red light camera locations with the automated speed enforcement technology.;13

column1: https://data.baltimorecity.gov/d/7egq-xgji;7egq-xgji;true;false;;data.baltimorecity.gov;dataset;Residential Parking Permits;The Baltimore RPP Program was begun in 1979 in an effort to address the specific needs of residents in city neighborhoods where the demand for on-street parking was considered to be greatest. Participating neighborhoods elect to do so through application by petition to the City of Baltimore through the Parking Authority of Baltimore City.Since its inception
column2: the RPP Program has grown to include 41 designated RPP areas
column3: each designated with its own specific number or letter. Parking in each of these 41 areas is restricted to some degree to provide preferential parking privileges only to those residents and their guests who display valid Residential Parking Permits and Visitors Passes on their automobiles. These permits and passes are issued and valid for a one-year period from the designated annual renewal date for each specific RPP Area. Residents must re-apply every year.;2
